{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868909/1930101701/0255.xml":{"full_text":"Page Three\nNO STATISTICS\nBACK HOOVER'S\nJOBLESS TALK\nBY LAURENCE TODD.\nWASHINGTON \u2014Herbert Hoo\nver\u2019s reckless use of statistics has\nbecome a stock joke in the capital,\nbut the country at large has not yet\nrealized that question marks must\nbe set down on either side of any\nset of figures which are presented\nby the former mine promoter. The\nFederated Press correspondent has\nagain been reminded of this fact\nby an assertion the president made\nin his speech to the convention of\nthe American Federation of Labor\nin Boston.\n\u201cWe still have a burden of un\nemployment,\u201d Hoover conceded.\n\u201cAlthough It is far less than one\nhalf in proportion to our workers\nthan in either England or Ger\nmany.\nHow did he get the idea, and why\ndid he assert as a fact, that Ameri\ncan unemployment is less than half\nas general a condition as in Eng\nland or Germany?\nHave no Statistics.\nInquiry began at the bureau of\nlabor statistics, where Hoover ought\nto have gone for any campaign\nstatement of that sort. If it were\ntrue that American workers have\ntwice the chance of getting and\nholding a job, this season, that Eng\nlish or German workers have, the\nbureau of labor statistics ought to\nbe able to point to official reports\nproving it. And if there were no\nsuch official figures, the president\nought not to assert them.\nBut Commissioner Stewart has no\nsuch figures. His bureau has none.\nThere are no reliable statistics on\nunemployment in this country, and\nthere are none that cover all the\nunemployed in Engalnd or Ger\nmany. Of course the bureau of la\nbor statistics is under the labor de\npartment, which has been engaged\nfor the past year in making James\n.1. Davis senator from Pennsylvania.\nDavis has proclaimed the return of\nprosperity and steady jobs, right\nalong. But he has not manufactured\n<.he figures Hoover used. Davis\nnever thought up so cheerful a pic\nture as that.\nKlein l|as no Figures.\nPerhaps, however, the radio opti\nmist, Julius Klein, adviser of Hoo\nver and assistant secretary of com\nmerce, had the figures. An inter\nview with Klein was negotiated.\nNo, Klein did not know where the\nclaim made by his chief came from.\nHe had never used such figures. He\ndid not believe there were accurate\nstatistics as to the number of un\nemployed in England or Germany.\nOf course the census figures an\nnounced some time ago showed that\nthere were 2,500,000 \u201cunemployed\nand looking for work and not find\ning it,\u201d in this country. But Klein\nadmitted that that figure repre\nsented only a portion of the total\nof American jobless.\nHfs subordinate, Dr. E. Dana\nDurand, economist and statistician,\nwas equally devoid of facts to sup\nport Hoover\u2019s claim, although he ex\npressed the personal opinion that\nunemployment in Europe is worse\nthan in America. That, he admitted,\nwas merely an opinion.\nSpeech Writing Absent.\nOoe chance remained\u2014that Hoo\nver\u2019s spe e c h-writing assistant,\nFrench Strother, had known some\nthing that led him to permit that\nclaim to go into the Hoover speech.\nBut Strother had sailed away to\nUncle Ray\u2019s Corner\nSPEEDWAYS OF THE FUTURE.\nDuring the past six months I\nhave visited most of the very large\ncities of the world\u2014including Lon\ndon, Paris, Vienna, Moscow, New\nYork and Chicago; and on every\nside I have seen need for better\ncare of the traffic problem.\nAutomobiles do not mix well with\npeople on the streets. The aver\nage speed of autos has greatly in\ncreased. About 25 years ago, a mo-\nNew York \u201cspeedway\u201d as seen from\nabove.\ntorist in New York was arrested for\ndriving \u201cat the reckless speed of\n17 miles an hour.\u201d Many drivers\nnow think that 17 miles an hour is\n\u201ccrawling along.\u201d\nMotorists want to get to places\nIn a hurry. People on the streets\ndo not enjoy being knocked over.\nWhat is to be done about it? The\nstreets now belong to people who\nwalk and to people who drive. Per\nhaps the time will come when they\nwill be devided up. so that some be\nlong to the drivers, and some to\nthe walkers.\nIn London, tunnels have been\nbuilt under a few streets, so that\nthose on foot can walk beneath the\ntraffic lines. That is one way of\nhelping out.\nIn New York a slight approach to\nUNCLE RAY\u2019S BIRTHDAY CLUB,\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER\nPlease enroll me in Uncle Kay\u2019s Birthday Club.\nMy name is\n1 will be...... ^^.jears on.\nStreet Address\nCity \u25a0llji i. i 11 1 t i inturr* r State HWHWWWH^wniiiiiiniiiiwiiiu*\u00bb\nCONVENTION OF\nLEGION CALLED\nDRUNKEN ORGY\nBy Federated Frets.\nBOSTON \u2014Official patriotic Bos\nton is all fussed up because Crim\nson, Harvard daily, described the\nAmerican legion convention just ad\njourned in Boston as a \u201cdrunken\norgy.\u201d Get togethers of the World\nwar officers, the student paper said,\nwere \u201cmerely an excuse for a\nwholesale brawl.\u201d The editorial\nheading was The Drunken Legion.\nAll patriots in town rushed to\nthe defense of the hard-drinking\nwarriors for democracy. One in\ndignant pastor, denying that the\nlegionnaires were any worse than\ncould be expected, admitted that\nthey had left whisky bottles in his\nchurch after attending a service\nthere.\nThe Statler hotel, legion head\nquarters, was said to have suffered\nheavy losses in damaged furniture,\nlights, mattresses, pillows and other\nmovable objects. Taxi men sighed\nwith relief as the last of the drunk\nen delegates reeled to the railway\nstation.\nLegionnaires thought it great fun\nto stick their canes into headlights,\ndome lights and taximeters. An\nacute shortage of pillows in the\nStatler followed the legionnaires\npractice of dumping the contents in\ncorridors or pitching them out of\nwindows. One legion defender de\nclared the ex-looies were creating\na \u2018national culture.\u2019\nSix Paintings Gift\nOf Grads to School\nThe 1930 graduates of the Bay\nView High school recently presented\nsix paintings to the school.\nThe pictures were selected by\nGustav A. Fritsche, principal.\nThree pictures were painted by\nRaymond Stelzner. a Milwaukee\nman, who is emploved by the Pre\nmier Engraving Co. These include\nA March Day, Looking Into the\nLight, The Bride at Waterford.\nOne of the paintings The Night\nWatch, Is the work of Rembrandt\nVan Ryne. The Sante Fe Trail by\nJohn Young Hunter and a landscape\nby Willard Metcalf were also pre\nsented.\nBermuda to give his tired brain a\nrest. His testimony on the jobless\nsituation here and in England and\nGermany could not be taken until\nlater in the campaign. But in the\nmeantime millions of American vot\ners would be resting secure in the\nbelief that Hoover was quoting gen\nuine statistics, and that really the\nunemployment situation in this\ncountry was not bad at all.\nOr would they? Had Hoover\novertaxed their faith, in the pres\nence of long lines of applicants for\njobs at the gates of such factories\nas were operating? \u201cCurtailed\nschedules\u201d was the burden of the\nmid-October report of the United\nStates employment service, from all\nover the nation. \u201cSurplus of work\ners\u201d was the refrain of returns from\nevery state.\nThose street crowds in Cleveland\nand Boston had been cold toward\nthe head of the administration.\nClergy were beginning to call upon\nmayors and governors to summon\nthe business magnates into confer\nence to provide food and shelter for\nthe army of unemployed when chill\nwinds blow and the snow begins to\nfall. Possibly Hoover bragged to\nkeep up a quaking courage. Polit\nical storm clouds were rolling omin\nously in his direction.\nsolving the problem has been made.\nA wide \u201cspeedway,\u201d high above the\nsidewalks, has been built for motor\ntraffic along the Hudson river.\nAnother problem of motor traffic\nis the two-way highway. A motor\nist may be driving along very hap\npily when an auto, coming in the\nopposite direction and trying to\npass another car darts into his\npath. Then there may be tragedy.\nA number of one-way highways\nhave been built within recent years,\nand these provide safer paths for\ntourists.\nAnother grave danger to motor\nists is the railway crossing. About\nG,OOO persons in the United States\nand Canada are killed each year at\nrailway crossings.\nTomorrow\u2014-A Little Saturday\nTalk.\nUncle Ray will be glad to send\nyou free of charge his leaflet con\ntaining 20 interesting questions\nabout Europe. Address Uncle Ray,\nin care of The Milwaukee Leader,\nand be sure to inclose a self-ad\ndressed, stamped envelope.\n(Copyright, 1930, Publishers\u2019 Syndicate.)\nUncle Ray\u2019s\nBirthday Club\nUnde Ray and The Milwaukee\nLeader wish a happy birthday to\nthe following:\nBirthday\u2014Oct. 17, 1930.\nLoraine Hodgin, 948 Winnebago\nst., 14 years.\nMathilda Stanke, 387 Sixteenth\nst., 13 years.\nEvelyn Hampel, 816 Thirty-second\nst., 13 years.\nNorman Zahn, 1387 Twenty-ninth\nst.. 10 years.\nFay Ann Link, 439 Fourteenth\nave., 7 years.\nFree\nParking\nThere\u2019s a free\nnarking station\nat each of The\nThree Schuster\nStores.\nMen\u2019s lB to 28 50 Overcoats\nI r flB\nU 1\nfl'\nF\nJ\nBoys\u2019 Suits\n2 Knickers!\n$9.95\n8 to 14 Years\nSmart wool suits that will give\namazing service and keen any\nboy smartly dressed. Tan,\nbrown and gray tweed mix\ntures. Tailored and stitched\nlike expensive suits!\nBoys\u2019 Warm Wool\nOvercoats $9.95\nSwagger double-breasted style\nwith plain or belted backs.\nNeat browns and grays...\nsizes 4 to 10. A lot of over\ncoat value for mother\u2019s\nmoney!\nBoys\u2019 Mannish\n\u201cLongies,\u201d $2.98\nWith the cut and the swag\nger that\u2019s typical of well-made\ntrousers. Of durable woolens\nin tan, brown and gray mix\ntures. Sizes 11 to 18.\nBoys\u2019 Clothing\u2014Second Floors\n--ml\n\u201cWhite Chief\u201d\nBoys\u2019 Sweaters\n$2-98\nk\nEven the roughest \u2